{"title_page": "Little Church Around the Corner (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1923 film directed by William A. Seiter}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Little Church Around the Corner\n| image          = Little Church Around the Corner (1923) - 2.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Film still\n| director       = [[William A. Seiter]]\n| producer       = \n| screenplay     = [[Olga Printzlau]]\n| story          = Charles E. Blaney \n| based on       = {{based on|''Little Church Around the Corner''|Marion Russell}}\n| starring       = [[Claire Windsor]]<br>[[Kenneth Harlan]]<br>[[Hobart Bosworth]]<br>[[Pauline Starke]]<br>[[Walter Long (actor)|Walter Long]]<br>[[Cyril Chadwick]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Edwin B. DuPar]]<br>[[Homer Scott]]\n| editing        = C.R. Wallace \n| studio         = [[Warner Bros.]]\n| distributor    = Warner Bros.\n| released       = {{Film date|1923|3|}}\n| runtime        = 70 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]] (English [[intertitle]]s)\n| budget         = $141,000<ref name=\"warners\">Warner Bros financial information in The William Shaefer Ledger. See Appendix 1, Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television, (1995) 15:sup1, 1-31 p 1 DOI: 10.1080/01439689508604551</ref>\n| gross          = $358,000<ref name=\"warners\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Little Church Around the Corner''''' is a 1923 American [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[William A. Seiter]] and written by [[Olga Printzlau]]. The film stars [[Claire Windsor]], [[Kenneth Harlan]], [[Hobart Bosworth]], [[Pauline Starke]], [[Walter Long (actor)|Walter Long]], and [[Cyril Chadwick]]. The film was released by [[Warner Bros.]] in March 1923.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/497539/Little-Church-Around-the-Corner/ |title=Little Church Around the Corner (1923) - Overview |publisher=TCM.com |date= |accessdate=2017-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Hal Erickson |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/little-church-around-the-corner-v29505 |title=Little Church Around the Corner (1923) - William Seiter |publisher=AllMovie |date= |accessdate=2017-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/10299 |title=Little Church Around the Corner |publisher=Catalog.afi.com |date= |accessdate=2017-12-04}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{Section empty|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Cast==    \n*[[Claire Windsor]] as Leila Morton\n*[[Kenneth Harlan]] as David Graham\n*[[Hobart Bosworth]] as John Morton\n*[[Pauline Starke]] as Hetty Burrows\n*[[Walter Long (actor)|Walter Long]] as Big Hex Poulon\n*[[Cyril Chadwick]] as Mark Hanford\n*[[Alec B. Francis]] as Reverend Bradley \n*[[Winter Hall]] as Doc\n*[[Margaret Seddon]] as Mrs. Wallace\n*[[George Cooper (actor)|George Cooper]] as Jude Burrows\n*[[Stanton Heck]] as Burt Wilson\n*[[Fred R. Stanton]] as The Sheriff \n*[[Winston Miller]] as Little David \n*[[Mary Jane Irving]] as Little Hetty\n\n==Box office==\nAccording to Warner Bros records the film earned $324,000 domestically and $28,000 foreign.<ref name=\"warners\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Little Church Around the Corner (1923 film)}}\n*{{IMDb title|0014202|Little Church Around the Corner}}\n*{{allmovie|29505|Synopsis}}\n\n{{William A. Seiter}}\n\n[[Category:1923 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:1920s drama films]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by William A. Seiter]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n\n\n{{1920s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1923 film directed by William A. Seiter}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Little Church Around the Corner\n| image          = Little Church Around the Corner (1923) - 2.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Film still\n| director       = [[William A. Seiter]]\n| producer       = \n| screenplay     = [[Olga Printzlau]]\n| story          = Charles E. Blaney \n| based on       = {{based on|''Little Church Around the Corner''|Marion Russell}}\n| starring       = [[Claire Windsor]]<br>[[Kenneth Harlan]]<br>[[Hobart Bosworth]]<br>[[Pauline Starke]]<br>[[Walter Long (actor)|Walter Long]]<br>[[Cyril Chadwick]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Edwin B. DuPar]]<br>[[Homer Scott]]\n| editing        = C.R. Wallace \n| studio         = [[Warner Bros.]]\n| distributor    = Warner Bros.\n| released       = {{Film date|1923|3|}}\n| runtime        = 70 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]] (English [[intertitle]]s)\n| budget         = $141,000<ref name=\"warners\">Warner Bros financial information in The William Shaefer Ledger. See Appendix 1, Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television, (1995) 15:sup1, 1-31 p 1 DOI: 10.1080/01439689508604551</ref>\n| gross          = $358,000<ref name=\"warners\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Little Church Around the Corner''''' is a 1923 American [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[William A. Seiter]] and written by [[Olga Printzlau]]. The film stars [[Claire Windsor]], [[Kenneth Harlan]], [[Hobart Bosworth]], [[Pauline Starke]], [[Walter Long (actor)|Walter Long]], and [[Cyril Chadwick]]. The film was released by [[Warner Bros.]] in March 1923.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/497539/Little-Church-Around-the-Corner/ |title=Little Church Around the Corner (1923) - Overview |publisher=TCM.com |date= |accessdate=2017-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Hal Erickson |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/little-church-around-the-corner-v29505 |title=Little Church Around the Corner (1923) - William Seiter |publisher=AllMovie |date= |accessdate=2017-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/10299 |title=Little Church Around the Corner |publisher=Catalog.afi.com |date= |accessdate=2017-12-04}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{Section empty|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Cast==    \n*[[Claire Windsor]] as Leila Morton\n*[[Kenneth Harlan]] as David Graham\n*[[Hobart Bosworth]] as John Morton\n*[[Pauline Starke]] as Hetty Burrows\n*[[Walter Long (actor)|Walter Long]] as Big Hex Poulon\n*[[Cyril Chadwick]] as Mark Hanford\n*[[Alec B. Francis]] as Reverend Bradley \n*[[Winter Hall]] as Doc\n*[[Margaret Seddon]] as Mrs. Wallace\n*[[George Cooper (actor)|George Cooper]] as Jude Burrows\n*[[Stanton Heck]] as Burt Wilson\n*[[Fred R. Stanton]] as The Sheriff \n*[[Winston Miller]] as Little David \n*[[Mary Jane Irving]] as Little Hetty\n\n==Box Office==\nAccording to Warner Bros records the film earned $324,000 domestically and $28,000 foreign.<ref name=\"warners\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Little Church Around the Corner (1923 film)}}\n*{{IMDb title|0014202|Little Church Around the Corner}}\n*{{allmovie|29505|Synopsis}}\n\n{{William A. Seiter}}\n\n[[Category:1923 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:1920s drama films]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by William A. Seiter]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n\n\n{{1920s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBox office:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little_Church_Around_the_Corner_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Harold Budd", "text_new": "{{short description|American avant-garde composer and poet|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{for|the Olympic rower|Harold Budd (rower)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name        = Harold Budd\n| image       = Harold Budd.jpg\n| caption       = {{longitem|Harold Budd in Japan<br/>{{smaller|(photo: Masao Nakagami)}}}}\n| background    = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name    = Harold Montgomory Budd\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1936|5|24|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| genre        = [[Ambient music|Ambient]], [[Drone music|drone]], [[Avant-garde music|avant-garde]], [[Neoclassicism (music)|neoclassical]]\n| occupation    = Musician, composer, poet, professor\n| instrument    = Piano, keyboards, guitar\n| years_active   = 1962\u2013present\n| label         = Opal, Land, [[Darla Records|Darla]], [[Samadhi Sound|Samadhi]], [[New World Records|New World]], [[All Saints Records|All Saints]], [[E.G. Records|EG]], 4AD\n| website       = {{URL|https://haroldbudd.com}} \n}}\n\n'''Harold Montgomory Budd''' (born May 24, 1936) is an American [[avant-garde]] composer and poet.<ref name=\"Baker's bio entry\">{{cite book |author1=Nicolas Slonimsky |author2=Laura Kuhn |author3=Dennis McIntire |authorlink1=Nicolas Slonimsky |title=Baker's Biographical Dictionary of Musicians |url-access=subscription  |via=[[HighBeam Research]] |date=January 1, 2001 |publisher=Schirmer Books |isbn=9780028655253 |edition=9th |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3491801863.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402194359/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3491801863.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 2, 2015 |accessdate=March 2, 2015}}</ref> He was born in Los Angeles and raised in the [[Mojave Desert]]. He has developed a style of playing piano he terms \"soft pedal\".\n\n==Early life==\nBudd was born in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] and spent his childhood in [[Victorville, California]] by the [[Mojave Desert]].<ref name=\"Audiophile\"/> While serving in the army, he joined the regimental band where he played drums. Jazz saxophonist [[Albert Ayler]] was drafted at the same time and  was also a member of the band. Budd joined him in gigs around the [[Monterey]] area.<ref name=\"Audiophile\">{{cite web|url=https://theaudiophileman.com/box-budd-talking-harold-budd/|title=A Box of Budd: Talking to Harold Budd|publisher=theaudiophileman.com|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Education and academic career==\nBudd's career as a composer began in 1962. In the following years, he gained a notable reputation in the local avant-garde community.<ref name=\"Leone\">{{cite web|url=https://fdleone.com/2016/05/24/harold-budd-utterly-no-interest-in-labels/|title=Harold Budd: utterly no interest in labels|publisher=FDLeone.com|accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref> In 1966, he graduated from the [[University of Southern California]] (having studied under [[Ingolf Dahl]]) with a degree in musical composition. As he progressed, his compositions became increasingly [[minimalism|minimalist]]. Among his more experimental works were two [[drone music]] pieces, \"Coeur d'Orr\" and \"The Oak of the Golden Dreams\". After composing a long-form [[gong]] solo titled \"Lirio\", he felt he had reached the limits of his experiments in minimalism and the avant-garde. He retired temporarily from composition in 1970 and began a teaching career at the [[California Institute of the Arts]].[http://www.nndb.com/people/738/000113399/ [1<nowiki>]</nowiki>]\n\n\"The road from my first colored graph piece in 1962 to my renunciation of composing in 1970 to my resurfacing as a composer in 1972 was a process of trying out an idea and when it was obviously successful abandoning it. The early graph piece was followed by the Rothko orchestra work, the pieces for ''Source Magazine'', the [[Morton Feldman|Feldman]]-derived chamber works, the pieces typed out or written in [[longhand]], the out-and-out conceptual works among other things, and the model drone works (which include the sax and organ \"Coeur d'Orr\" and \"The Oak of the Golden Dreams\", the latter based on the [[Bali]]nese \"[[Slendro]]\" scale which scale I used again 18 years later on \"The Real Dream of Sails\").<ref name=\"Leone\"/>\n\n\"In 1970 with the \"Candy-Apple Revision\" (unspecified D-flat major) and \"Lirio\" (solo gong \"for a long duration\") I realized I had minimalized myself out of a career. It had taken ten years to reduce my language to zero but I loved the process of seeing it occur and not knowing when the end would come. By then I had opted out of avant-garde music generally; it seemed self-congratulatory and risk-free and my solution as to what to do next was to do nothing, to stop completely.\"\n\n\"I resurfaced as an artist in 1972 with \"Madrigals of the Rose Angel\", the first of what would be a cycle of works under the collective title ''[[The Pavilion of Dreams]]''. ''Madrigals'' refused to accommodate or even acknowledge any issues in new music. The entire aesthetic was an existential prettiness; not the [[Plato]]nic \"to Kalon\", but simply pretty: mindless, shallow and utterly devastating. Female chorus, harp and percussion seemed like a beautiful start. Its first performance was at a Franciscan church in California conducted by [[Daniel Lentz]].\"<ref >{{Cite AV media notes |title=The Pavilion of Dreams|title-link=The Pavilion of Dreams |year=1992|page=2|type=booklet |publisher=EG}} </ref>\n\n==Composer and recording artist==\nIn 1972, while still retaining his teaching career, he resurfaced as a composer. Spanning from 1972\u20131975 he created four individual works under the collective title \"The Pavilion of Dreams\". The style of these works was an unusual blend of popular jazz and the avant-garde. In 1976 he resigned from the institute and began recording his new compositions, produced by British ambient pioneer [[Brian Eno]]. Two years later, Harold Budd's debut album ''The Pavilion of Dreams'' was released.\n\nBudd has developed a style of playing piano he terms \"soft pedal,\" which can be described as slow and sustained. While he is often placed in the Ambient category, he emphatically declares that he is not an Ambient artist, and feels that he got \"kidnapped\" into the category.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hoffer|first=Jason|title=Drinking Scotch, smoking cigarettes, and hanging out with Feldman, Rothko and Budd|url=http://goingthruvinyl.com/wp/2012/06/drinking-scotch-smoking-cigerettes-and-hanging-out-with-feldman-rothko-and-budd-listen-3700s02-ep11-part-1-of-2/|publisher=Going Thru Vinyl Ltd.|accessdate=September 21, 2012|author2=Harold Budd|location=9:00|format=audio (mp3)}}</ref> His two collaborations with Brian Eno, ''[[The Plateaux of Mirror]]'' and ''[[The Pearl (album)|The Pearl]]'', established his trademark atmospheric piano style. On ''[[Lovely Thunder]]'' he introduced subtle electronic textures. His thematic 2000 release ''[[The Room (album)|The Room]]'' saw a return to a more minimalist approach. In 2003, [[Daniel Lanois]], the renowned producer of [[U2]] and [[Bob Dylan]], and occasional collaborator with Brian Eno, recorded an impromptu performance of Harold playing the piano in his Los Angeles living room, unaware, and thus realized the album ''La Bella Vista''.\n\nHis album ''[[Avalon Sutra / As Long as I Can Hold My Breath|Avalon Sutra]]'' from 2004 was billed as \"Harold Budd's Last Recorded Work\" by [[David Sylvian]]'s independent record label [[Samadhi Sound|Samadhisound]]. Their press release continued: \"''Avalon Sutra'' brings to a conclusion thirty years of sustained musical activity. Asked for his reasons, Budd says only that he feels that he has said what he has to say. With characteristic humility, he concludes, \"I don\u2019t mind disappearing!\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samadhisound.com/archive/harold_budd_avalon_sutra.html|title=Harold Budd \"Avalon Sutra\"|publisher=Samadhisound.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref> A farewell concert retrospective was performed at The Disney Theater/REDCAT in Los Angeles in September 2004 with Budd playing solo and with guests [[Jon Gibson (minimalist musician)|Jon Gibson]], [[Clive Wright (musician)|Clive Wright]] and more. It featured music from Budd's \"Avalon Sutra\", and as far back as \"Lirio\". A second farewell concert featuring Budd and guest-starring many of the musicians he had worked with throughout his career was presented at [[Brighton Dome]] in May 2005, also billed as being Budd's last public performance. In spite of this, Budd's soundtrack to the film [[Mysterious Skin - Music from the Film|''Mysterious Skin'']] (a collaboration with [[Robin Guthrie]]) and ''[[Music for 'Fragments from the Inside']]'' (with [[Eraldo Bernocchi]]) were both released in 2005.\n\nIn February 2007, Samadhisound released ''Perhaps'', a live recording of Budd's improvised performance at CalArts on December 6, 2006 in tribute to his late friend (and associate teacher at the then newly formed [[California Institute of Arts]]) [[James Tenney]].\n\nIn April 2007, Samadhisound released a podcast of Harold Budd in conversation with [[Akira Rabelais]]. In this (Samadhisound Podcast #2), Harold said although he had believed at the time of recording ''Avalon Sutra'' that it would be his last album, he no longer felt that way. \"It was a time in my life when things weren't just falling together for me, and I thought that I was just going to let it all slide ... and I was sincere about it but if I had been more conscious of my real feelings and had explored my inner sanctum more I would've seen that it was a preposterous thing to do ... I was dreadfully lonely; I was living alone in the desert and had been for too long, really, and I felt that isolation very severely after a while, and it's probably a version of self-pity, I'm sorry to say, to have publicly said something like that, but there it is, I said it, turns out I wasn't telling the truth \u2013 I didn't know it at the time.\"\n\nIn June 2007, [[Darla Records]] released two CDs by Robin Guthrie and Harold Budd: ''[[After the Night Falls]]'' and ''[[Before the Day Breaks]]''. Recorded in Spring 2006, each features nine tracks with linked titles, e.g. \"How Distant Your Heart\"/\"How Close Your Soul\" and \"I Returned Her Glance\"/\"And Then I Turned Away\".<ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/robin-guthrie-harold-budd-after-the-night-falls/|title=\nRobin Guthrie & Harold Budd After the Night Falls|publisher=popmatters.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2008, Darla Records released a collaboration with Clive Wright entitled ''Song for Lost Blossoms''. It includes recordings that were done live and in-studio at different locations, including both artists' homes. The album features some of their work done together between 2004 and 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://darla.com/index.php?fuseaction=item_cat.ecom_superitem_detail&item_cat_id=62|title=Harold Budd & Clive Wright \u2013 A Song for Lost Blossoms (Darla) |publisher=Darla.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref> A second collaborative effort with Wright, ''Candylion'' followed in 2009, again on Darla Records.\n\nIn February 2011, Darla Records released a CD album by Robin Guthrie and Harold Budd entitled ''Bordeaux'', recorded in the summer of 2010 in Bordeaux, France and mixed in Guthrie's studio, in Rennes, France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://darla.com/index.php?fuseaction=item_cat.ecom_superitem_detail&item_cat_id=3894|title=Robin Guthrie & Harold Budd \u2013 Bordeaux (Darla) |publisher=Darla.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, [[Eraldo Bernocchi]]'s RareNoiseRecords released a CD album by Eraldo Bernocchi, Harold Budd, Robin Guthrie entitled ''Winter Garden'', recorded in the summer of 2010 in Tuscany, Italy and mixed in Guthrie's studio, in Rennes, France.<ref name=\"Guthrie\">{{cite web|url=http://www.robinguthrie.com/|title=News|publisher=Robinguthrie.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, Budd appeared as one of the featured composer/performers at San Francisco's [[Other Minds (organization)|Other Minds]] festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otherminds.org/home.htm|title=Other Minds|work=otherminds.org|access-date=November 14, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127162620/http://www.otherminds.org/home.htm|archive-date=November 27, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he collaborated with [[Robin Guthrie]] while working on the soundtrack for [[White Bird in a Blizzard]]. The actual score used in the film was not released. [[Lakeshore Records]] released an album with the original score accept \"The Affair\".\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Harold Budd discography}}\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''The Oak of the Golden Dreams / Coeur D'Orr'' (1970) Advance Recordings\n* ''[[The Pavilion of Dreams]]'' (1978) E.G. Records produced by Brian Eno<ref name=\"Progarchives\">{{cite web|url=http://www.progarchives.com/artist.asp?id=5471|title=Harold Budd discography|publisher=Progarchives.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Ambient 2: [[The Plateaux of Mirror]]'' (1980) E.G. Records with Brian Eno<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''The Serpent (In Quicksilver)'' (1981) Cantil<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[The Pearl (album)|The Pearl]]'' (1984) E.G. Records with Brian Eno<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''Abandoned Cities'' (1984) Cantil<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[Lovely Thunder]]'' (1986) E.G. Records produced by Michael Hoenig<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[The White Arcades]]'' (1988) Opal Records produced by Brian Eno<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[Agua (album)|Agua]]'' (1989) Opal Records recorded live at the Lanzarote Music Festival<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[By the Dawn's Early Light]]'' (1991) Opal Records with [[Bill Nelson (musician)|Bill Nelson]], [[B.J. Cole]], [[Susan Allen (musician)|Susan Allen]]<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[Music for 3 Pianos]]'' (1992) All Saints Records with Ruben Garcia and Daniel Lentz\n* ''She Is a Phantom'' (1994) New Albion with Zeitgeist<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''Through the Hill'' (1994) All Saints Records with Andy Partridge<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[Luxa (album)|Luxa]]'' (1996) All Saints Records<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''Walk into My Voice: American Beat Poetry'' (1996) Materiali Sonori with Daniel Lentz & Jessica Karraker\n* ''Fenceless Night: Selections for Cinema 1980\u20131998'' compilation, promotional only (1998) Polygram\n* ''[[The Room (album)|The Room]]'' (2000) Atlantic Records<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''Three White Roses & A Budd'' (2002) {{nowrap|Twentythree Records}} with Bill Nelson & {{nowrap|[[Fila Brazillia]]}} \n* ''Jah Wobble's Solaris \u2013 Live in Concert'' (2002) 30 Hertz Records with Jah Wobble, Graham Haynes, Jaki Liebezeit & Bill Laswell \n* ''La Bella Vista'' (2003) [[Shout Factory]]<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[Translucence/Drift Music]]'' (2003) Edsel Records with John Foxx<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[Avalon Sutra / As Long as I Can Hold My Breath]]'' 2-CD digipak (2004) [[Samadhi Sound|Samadhisound]] produced by Harold Budd<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[Mysterious Skin \u2013 Music from the Film]]'' (2005) Commotion Records/Rykodisc with Robin Guthrie<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''Music for 'Fragments from the Inside''' (2005) Sub Rosa with [[Eraldo Bernocchi]]\n* ''Perhaps'' (2007) Samadhisound (Live album)<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''After the Night Falls'' (2007) Darla Records with Robin Guthrie<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''Before the Day Breaks'' (2007) Darla Records with Robin Guthrie<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''A Song for Lost Blossoms'' (2008) Darla Records with Clive Wright<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''Candylion'' (2009) Darla Records with Clive Wright<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''Little Windows'' (2010) Darla Records with Clive Wright<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''Nighthawks, Translucence and Drift Music'' 37-track, 3-CD digipak (2011) Edsel Records with John Foxx\n* ''Bordeaux'' (2011) Darla Records with Robin Guthrie<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''Winter Garden'' (2011) RareNoiseRecords with Robin Guthrie & Eraldo Bernocchi<ref name=\"Guthrie\"/>\n* ''In the Mist'' (2011) Darla Records<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''Bandits of Stature'' (2012) Darla Records, P Toyon Music (BMI), distributed in the US by Caroline Records, Inc.\n* ''Jane 1\u201311'' (2013) Darla Records\n* ''Wind in Lonely Fences 1970 \u2013 2011'' 18-track, 2-CD digipak (2013) All Saints Records with Cocteau Twins and Robin Guthrie, John Foxx, & Brian Eno\n* ''Buddbox'' anthology box set containing 7 hard-to-find and critically acclaimed albums (2013) All Saints Records\n* \"Buddbox Sampler\" Limited edition 15-track promo sampler for the 7 CD Buddbox anthology box set (2013) All Saints Records\n* ''Jane 12\u201321'' (2014) Darla Records\n* ''[[White Bird in a Blizzard]]'' (2014) Lakeshore Records with Robin Guthrie<ref name=\"Guthrie\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Brian Eno]]\n* [[Experimental music]]\n*[[List of ambient music artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://haroldbudd.com/ Harold Budd] Home page\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091009012653/http://www.newalbion.com/artists/buddh/index.htm New Albion Records] Harold Budd page\n* [http://www.samadhisound.com/haroldbudd/ Samadhisound] Harold Budd page\n* [http://www.sleepbot.com/ambience/page/budd.html Ambience for the Masses] Harold Budd page\n* [https://pages.bookstellyouwhy.com/harold-budd Books Tell You Why] Harold Budd: His Life & Works\n* [http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/jan97/haroldbudd.html Harold Budd: American Vision] article from Sound on Sound magazine\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070513050114/http://www.soundnet.org/concerts/mov_refs/2004.shtml#budd soundNET Concert Archives] A rare live performance of works by Harold Budd (September 18, 2004) [streaming QuickTime audio]\n* [http://www.eleventhvolume.com/reviews/concerts/files/harold_budd.html Somnambule] Review of Harold Budd \"Farewell Concert\" at Brighton Dome (May 21, 2005)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927210640/http://arts.independent.co.uk/music/features/article220720.ece Harold Budd: Harold in May] article from [[The Independent]] (May 8, 2005)\n* [http://goingthruvinyl.com/wp/2012/06/drinking-scotch-smoking-cigerettes-and-hanging-out-with-feldman-rothko-and-budd-listen-3700s02-ep11-part-1-of-2/ Audio interview with Going Thru Vinyl (Part 1)] (May 3, 2012)\n* [http://goingthruvinyl.com/wp/2012/07/harold-budd-interview-part-2-of-2-watching-sunlight-and-shadows-through-six-windows-with-harold-budd-s02-ep11/ Audio interview with Going Thru Vinyl (Part 2)] (May 3, 2012)\n\n{{Harold Budd}}\n{{Brian Eno}}\n{{Robin Guthrie}}\n{{Cocteau Twins}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Budd, Harold}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Thornton School of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:Ambient musicians]]\n[[Category:New-age musicians]]\n[[Category:American electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:American experimental musicians]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Record producers from California]]\n[[Category:All Saints Records artists]]\n[[Category:E.G. Records artists]]\n[[Category:4AD artists]]\n[[Category:Samadhi Sound artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:American male pianists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Victorville, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American avant-garde composer and poet|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{for|the Olympic rower|Harold Budd (rower)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name        = Harold Budd\n| image       = Harold Budd.jpg\n| caption       = {{longitem|Harold Budd in Japan<br/>{{smaller|(photo: Masao Nakagami)}}}}\n| background    = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name    = Harold Montgomory Budd\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1936|5|24|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| genre        = [[Ambient music|Ambient]], [[Drone music|drone]], [[Avant-garde music|avant-garde]], [[Neoclassicism (music)|neoclassical]]\n| occupation    = Musician, composer, poet, professor\n| instrument    = Piano, keyboards, guitar\n| years_active   = 1962\u2013present\n| label         = Opal, Land, [[Darla Records|Darla]], [[Samadhi Sound|Samadhi]], [[New World Records|New World]], [[All Saints Records|All Saints]], [[E.G. Records|EG]], 4AD\n| website       = {{URL|https://haroldbudd.com}} \n}}\n\n'''Harold Montgomory Budd''' (born May 24, 1936) is an American [[avant-garde]] composer and poet.<ref name=\"Baker's bio entry\">{{cite book |author1=Nicolas Slonimsky |author2=Laura Kuhn |author3=Dennis McIntire |authorlink1=Nicolas Slonimsky |title=Baker's Biographical Dictionary of Musicians |url-access=subscription  |via=[[HighBeam Research]] |date=January 1, 2001 |publisher=Schirmer Books |isbn=9780028655253 |edition=9th |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3491801863.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402194359/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3491801863.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 2, 2015 |accessdate=March 2, 2015}}</ref> He was born in Los Angeles and raised in the [[Mojave Desert]]. He has developed a style of playing piano he terms \"soft pedal\".\n\n==Early life==\nBudd was born in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] and spent his childhood in [[Victorville, California]] by the [[Mojave Desert]].<ref name=\"Audiophile\"/> While serving in the army, he joined the regimental band where he played drums. Jazz saxophonist [[Albert Ayler]] was drafted at the same time and  was also a member of the band. Budd joined him in gigs around the [[Monterey]] area.<ref name=\"Audiophile\">{{cite web|url=https://theaudiophileman.com/box-budd-talking-harold-budd/|title=A Box of Budd: Talking to Harold Budd|publisher=theaudiophileman.com|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Education and academic career==\nBudd's career as a composer began in 1962. In the following years, he gained a notable reputation in the local avant-garde community.<ref name=\"Leone\">{{cite web|url=https://fdleone.com/2016/05/24/harold-budd-utterly-no-interest-in-labels/|title=Harold Budd: utterly no interest in labels|publisher=FDLeone.com|accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref> In 1966, he graduated from the [[University of Southern California]] (having studied under [[Ingolf Dahl]]) with a degree in musical composition. As he progressed, his compositions became increasingly [[minimalism|minimalist]]. Among his more experimental works were two [[drone music]] pieces, \"Coeur d'Orr\" and \"The Oak of the Golden Dreams\". After composing a long-form [[gong]] solo titled \"Lirio\", he felt he had reached the limits of his experiments in minimalism and the avant-garde. He retired temporarily from composition in 1970 and began a teaching career at the [[California Institute of the Arts]].[http://www.nndb.com/people/738/000113399/ [1<nowiki>]</nowiki>]\n\n\"The road from my first colored graph piece in 1962 to my renunciation of composing in 1970 to my resurfacing as a composer in 1972 was a process of trying out an idea and when it was obviously successful abandoning it. The early graph piece was followed by the Rothko orchestra work, the pieces for ''Source Magazine'', the [[Morton Feldman|Feldman]]-derived chamber works, the pieces typed out or written in [[longhand]], the out-and-out conceptual works among other things, and the model drone works (which include the sax and organ \"Coeur d'Orr\" and \"The Oak of the Golden Dreams\", the latter based on the [[Bali]]nese \"[[Slendro]]\" scale which scale I used again 18 years later on \"The Real Dream of Sails\").<ref name=\"Leone\"/>\n\n\"In 1970 with the \"Candy-Apple Revision\" (unspecified D-flat major) and \"Lirio\" (solo gong \"for a long duration\") I realized I had minimalized myself out of a career. It had taken ten years to reduce my language to zero but I loved the process of seeing it occur and not knowing when the end would come. By then I had opted out of avant-garde music generally; it seemed self-congratulatory and risk-free and my solution as to what to do next was to do nothing, to stop completely.\"\n\n\"I resurfaced as an artist in 1972 with \"Madrigals of the Rose Angel\", the first of what would be a cycle of works under the collective title ''[[The Pavilion of Dreams]]''. ''Madrigals'' refused to accommodate or even acknowledge any issues in new music. The entire aesthetic was an existential prettiness; not the [[Plato]]nic \"to Kalon\", but simply pretty: mindless, shallow and utterly devastating. Female chorus, harp and percussion seemed like a beautiful start. Its first performance was at a Franciscan church in California conducted by [[Daniel Lentz]].\"<ref >{{Cite AV media notes |title=The Pavilion of Dreams|title-link=The Pavilion of Dreams |year=1992|page=2|type=booklet |publisher=EG}} </ref>\n\n==Composer and recording artist==\nIn 1972, while still retaining his teaching career, he resurfaced as a composer. Spanning from 1972\u20131975 he created four individual works under the collective title \"The Pavilion of Dreams\". The style of these works was an unusual blend of popular jazz and the avant-garde. In 1976 he resigned from the institute and began recording his new compositions, produced by British ambient pioneer [[Brian Eno]]. Two years later, Harold Budd's debut album ''The Pavilion of Dreams'' was released.\n\nBudd has developed a style of playing piano he terms \"soft pedal,\" which can be described as slow and sustained. While he is often placed in the Ambient category, he emphatically declares that he is not an Ambient artist, and feels that he got \"kidnapped\" into the category.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hoffer|first=Jason|title=Drinking Scotch, smoking cigarettes, and hanging out with Feldman, Rothko and Budd|url=http://goingthruvinyl.com/wp/2012/06/drinking-scotch-smoking-cigerettes-and-hanging-out-with-feldman-rothko-and-budd-listen-3700s02-ep11-part-1-of-2/|publisher=Going Thru Vinyl Ltd.|accessdate=September 21, 2012|author2=Harold Budd|location=9:00|format=audio (mp3)}}</ref> His two collaborations with Brian Eno, ''[[The Plateaux of Mirror]]'' and ''[[The Pearl (album)|The Pearl]]'', established his trademark atmospheric piano style. On ''[[Lovely Thunder]]'' he introduced subtle electronic textures. His thematic 2000 release ''[[The Room (album)|The Room]]'' saw a return to a more minimalist approach. In 2003, [[Daniel Lanois]], the renowned producer of [[U2]] and [[Bob Dylan]], and occasional collaborator with Brian Eno, recorded an impromptu performance of Harold playing the piano in his Los Angeles living room, unaware, and thus realized the album ''La Bella Vista''.\n\nHis album ''[[Avalon Sutra / As Long as I Can Hold My Breath|Avalon Sutra]]'' from 2004 was billed as \"Harold Budd's Last Recorded Work\" by [[David Sylvian]]'s independent record label [[Samadhi Sound|Samadhisound]]. Their press release continued: \"''Avalon Sutra'' brings to a conclusion thirty years of sustained musical activity. Asked for his reasons, Budd says only that he feels that he has said what he has to say. With characteristic humility, he concludes, \"I don\u2019t mind disappearing!\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samadhisound.com/archive/harold_budd_avalon_sutra.html|title=Harold Budd \"Avalon Sutra\"|publisher=Samadhisound.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref> A farewell concert retrospective was performed at The Disney Theater/REDCAT in Los Angeles in September 2004 with Budd playing solo and with guests [[Jon Gibson (minimalist musician)|Jon Gibson]], [[Clive Wright (musician)|Clive Wright]] and more. It featured music from Budd's \"Avalon Sutra\", and as far back as \"Lirio\". A second farewell concert featuring Budd and guest-starring many of the musicians he had worked with throughout his career was presented at [[Brighton Dome]] in May 2005, also billed as being Budd's last public performance. In spite of this, Budd's soundtrack to the film [[Mysterious Skin - Music from the Film|''Mysterious Skin'']] (a collaboration with [[Robin Guthrie]]) and ''[[Music for 'Fragments from the Inside']]'' (with [[Eraldo Bernocchi]]) were both released in 2005.\n\nIn February 2007, Samadhisound released ''Perhaps'', a live recording of Budd's improvised performance at CalArts on December 6, 2006 in tribute to his late friend (and associate teacher at the then newly formed [[California Institute of Arts]]) [[James Tenney]].\n\nIn April 2007, Samadhisound released a podcast of Harold Budd in conversation with [[Akira Rabelais]]. In this (Samadhisound Podcast #2), Harold said although he had believed at the time of recording ''Avalon Sutra'' that it would be his last album, he no longer felt that way. \"It was a time in my life when things weren't just falling together for me, and I thought that I was just going to let it all slide ... and I was sincere about it but if I had been more conscious of my real feelings and had explored my inner sanctum more I would've seen that it was a preposterous thing to do ... I was dreadfully lonely; I was living alone in the desert and had been for too long, really, and I felt that isolation very severely after a while, and it's probably a version of self-pity, I'm sorry to say, to have publicly said something like that, but there it is, I said it, turns out I wasn't telling the truth \u2013 I didn't know it at the time.\"\n\nIn June 2007, [[Darla Records]] released two CDs by Robin Guthrie and Harold Budd: ''[[After the Night Falls]]'' and ''[[Before the Day Breaks]]''. Recorded in Spring 2006, each features nine tracks with linked titles, e.g. \"How Distant Your Heart\"/\"How Close Your Soul\" and \"I Returned Her Glance\"/\"And Then I Turned Away\".<ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/robin-guthrie-harold-budd-after-the-night-falls/|title=\nRobin Guthrie & Harold Budd After the Night Falls|publisher=popmatters.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2008, Darla Records released a collaboration with Clive Wright entitled ''Song for Lost Blossoms''. It includes recordings that were done live and in-studio at different locations, including both artists' homes. The album features some of their work done together between 2004 and 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://darla.com/index.php?fuseaction=item_cat.ecom_superitem_detail&item_cat_id=62|title=Harold Budd & Clive Wright \u2013 A Song for Lost Blossoms (Darla) |publisher=Darla.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref> A second collaborative effort with Wright, ''Candylion'' followed in 2009, again on Darla Records.\n\nIn February 2011, Darla Records released a CD album by Robin Guthrie and Harold Budd entitled ''Bordeaux'', recorded in the summer of 2010 in Bordeaux, France and mixed in Guthrie's studio, in Rennes, France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://darla.com/index.php?fuseaction=item_cat.ecom_superitem_detail&item_cat_id=3894|title=Robin Guthrie & Harold Budd \u2013 Bordeaux (Darla) |publisher=Darla.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, [[Eraldo Bernocchi]]'s RareNoiseRecords released a CD album by Eraldo Bernocchi, Harold Budd, Robin Guthrie entitled ''Winter Garden'', recorded in the summer of 2010 in Tuscany, Italy and mixed in Guthrie's studio, in Rennes, France.<ref name=\"Guthrie\">{{cite web|url=http://www.robinguthrie.com/|title=News|publisher=Robinguthrie.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, Budd appeared as one of the featured composer/performers at San Francisco's [[Other Minds (organization)|Other Minds]] festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otherminds.org/home.htm|title=Other Minds|work=otherminds.org|access-date=November 14, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127162620/http://www.otherminds.org/home.htm|archive-date=November 27, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he collaborated with [[Robin Guthrie]] while working on the soundtrack for [[White Bird in a Blizzard]]. The actual score used in the film was not released. [[Lakeshore Records]] released an album with the original score accept the \"The Affair\".\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Harold Budd discography}}\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''The Oak of the Golden Dreams / Coeur D'Orr'' (1970) Advance Recordings\n* ''[[The Pavilion of Dreams]]'' (1978) E.G. Records produced by Brian Eno<ref name=\"Progarchives\">{{cite web|url=http://www.progarchives.com/artist.asp?id=5471|title=Harold Budd discography|publisher=Progarchives.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Ambient 2: [[The Plateaux of Mirror]]'' (1980) E.G. Records with Brian Eno<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''The Serpent (In Quicksilver)'' (1981) Cantil<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[The Pearl (album)|The Pearl]]'' (1984) E.G. Records with Brian Eno<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''Abandoned Cities'' (1984) Cantil<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[Lovely Thunder]]'' (1986) E.G. Records produced by Michael Hoenig<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[The White Arcades]]'' (1988) Opal Records produced by Brian Eno<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[Agua (album)|Agua]]'' (1989) Opal Records recorded live at the Lanzarote Music Festival<ref name=\"Progarchives\"/>\n* ''[[By the Dawn's Early Light]]'' (1991) Opal Records with [