{"title_page": "List of St. John's College (Annapolis/Santa Fe) people", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2014}}\nThe following is a list of notable individuals associated with [[St. John's College (Annapolis/Santa Fe)|St. John's College in Annapolis, Maryland and/or Santa Fe, New Mexico]].\n\n{{dynamic list}}\n\n<!-- NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * *NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE\nOnly people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here as notable people. This establishes notability. The person's biographical article should say how they are associated with the university. An external reliable source of their association should be cited in their article and here. All others will be deleted without further explanation. Alphabetize by last name, please. Use a short, one-line description of notability (no period). If the person you think is notable does not have a Wikipedia article for themselves, create one. Guidelines for the notability of a person can be found by entering WP:PEOPLE in the wiki search. Guidelines on what is needed and how to write the article can be found  by entering WP:MOSBIO in the wiki search.\nEND OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * END OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * *END OF NOTICE\n-->\n<!-- DO NOT ADD PEOPLE TO THIS LIST WITHOUT A VERIFIABLE CITATION.\nAdditions without a citation are subject to removal. \nIf a citation link is broken, please replace it with one that works.\n-->\n== Faculty ==\n* [[Douglas Allanbrook]], tutor, musician and composer<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Local Singers Elect Mrs. Beall|date=11 October 1954|work=The Capital (Annapolis, Maryland|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Wye Jamison Allanbrook]], tutor, musicologist\n* [[Eva Brann]], tutor, dean; 2005 recipient of the [[National Humanities Medal]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Harty|first=Rosemary|title=Bush Awards National Humanities Medal to St. John's College Tutor|publisher=CollegeNews.org|date=November 15, 2005|url=http://www.collegenews.org/x5062.xml|accessdate=8 December 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051124092133/http://www.collegenews.org/x5062.xml|archivedate=24 November 2005}}</ref>\n* [[James M. Cain]], novelist; professor of journalism 1923\u201324<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/543/000104231|title=Notable Names Database|accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=James M. Cain, 85, the Author of 'Postman Always Rings Twice'|last=Leonard|first=John|date=October 29, 1977|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n* [[Elliott Carter]], composer; tutor, 1939\u20131941\n* [[William Hersey Hopkins]] academic, first president of [[Goucher College]], former acting president of [[St. John's College (Annapolis/Santa Fe)|St. John's College]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=St. John's College Presidents|date=19 May 1949|work=The Capital (Annapolis, Maryland)|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Leon Kass]], tutor at the college (1972\u201376); chair of the [[President's Council on Bioethics]] (2002\u201306)\n* [[Jacob Klein (philosopher)|Jacob Klein]], tutor, dean; author of ''Greek Mathematical Thought and the Origin of Algebra'' and ''Commentary on Plato's Meno''; leading 20th-century Platonist\n* [[Sara Larkin]], artist; creator of ''Spacescapes''\n* [[Leo Strauss]] (1899\u20131973), political philosopher; lectured at St. John's and was the Scott Buchanan Distinguished Scholar in Residence at the Annapolis campus\n* [[Victor Zuckerkandl]], music theorist\n== Students and Alumni ==\n\n==== Academics ====\n\n* [[Rogers Albritton]], philosopher; served as the chairman of both Harvard and UCLA's philosophy departments\n* [[Joseph J. Himmel]], Jesuit missionary and president of [[Georgetown University]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woodstock College|author-link=Woodstock College|date=February 1, 1925|title=Obituary: Father Joseph J. Himmel|url=https://jesuitonlinelibrary.bc.edu/?a=d&d=wlet19250201-01.2.10|url-status=live|journal=Woodstock Letters|volume=54|issue=1|page=89|archive-url=https://jesuitonlinelibrary.bc.edu/?a=d&d=wlet19250201-01.2.10&dliv=none&st=1&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN-------|archive-date=December 30, 2018|access-date=December 30, 2018|ref=harv|via=Jesuit Online Library}}</ref>\n* [[Thomas J.J. Altizer]], theologian, author of ''The Gospel of Christian Atheism''\n* [[John Bremer]], educator, philosopher, author; after graduating from [[Oxford University]], he came to St. John's College in 1951 on a Fulbright Fellowship\n* [[Mark D. Jordan]], alumnus; [[Andrew Mellon]] Professor, [[Harvard Divinity School]]; scholar of [[gender studies]], [[sexual ethics]], and [[theology]]\n* [[Wilfred M. McClay]], intellectual historian\n* [[Ange Mlinko]], poet and critic. Guggenheim Fellow 2014-15, Poetry Editor of the [[The Nation|Nation]], associate professor at the [[University of Florida]]<ref>https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/ange-mlinko</ref>\n* [[Tom G. Palmer]], Senior Fellow at the [[Cato Institute]]\n*[[Pamela Sklar]] (1959\u20132017), psychiatrist and neuroscientist\n*[[Louis Leo Snyder]] (1907\u20131993), German scholar and historian\n\n==== Writers, Critics, and Journalists ====\n\n*[[Michael Anton]], writer; Former Deputy Assistant to the President for Strategic Communications.\n*[[David Berman (musician)|David Berman]] poet; Author ''Actual Air'', singer/songwriter with [[Silver Jews]].{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n*[[Seth Cropsey]], Director of the Center for American Seapower at the [[Hudson Institute]]; regular contributor to the ''National Review''\n*[[Robert A. George (pundit)|Robert A. George]], journalist and news columnist\n*[[William Kowalski]], author, ''Eddie's Bastard'', ''Somewhere South of Here'', ''The Adventures of Flash Jackson'', ''The Good Neighbor''\n*[[Kenneth Kronberg]], printing company owner, former [[LaRouche movement]] member<ref name=\"WPostobit\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/04/30/AR2007043001772_pf.html \"Kenneth L. Kronberg Sterling Businessman\"], ''The Washington Post'', May 1, 2007.</ref>\n*[[Tony Lagouranis]], activist and author of ''Fear Up Harsh: An Army Interrogator's Dark Journey through Iraq''\n*[[Lydia Polgreen]], Editor-in-Chief for ''[[The Huffington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/lydia-polgreen-huffington-post_us_5846ef54e4b0fe5ab693122b|title=Lydia Polgreen Named Editor-In-Chief Of The Huffington Post|date=2016-12-06|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=2016-12-06}}</ref> 2006 winner of the [[George Polk Award]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studyinternational.com/news/st-johns-college-driving-positive-graduate-outcomes/|title=St. John\u2019s College: Driving positive graduate outcomes|date=2018-01-22|website=Study International|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n*[[James Portnow]] writer, game designer, co-founder of the [[Extra Credits]] youtube channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digipen.edu/showcase/news/the-many-roles-of-james-portnow|title=The Many Roles of James Portnow|date=2018-06-26|website=DigiPen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n*[[Salvatore Scibona]], alumnus and author, 2008 [[National Book Award]] finalist for his first novel ''The End''; his fiction has appeared in many literary journals; named one of \"20 under 40\" notable authors by ''[[The New Yorker]]'' in 2010 and published an essay about his experience at the college in the June 13, 2011 issue<ref>[http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2011/06/13/110613fa_fact_scibona Profile of Scibona in ''The New Yorker''], June 13, 2011</ref>\n*[[Lisa Simeone]], [[National Public Radio]] host<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=2101205|title=Lisa Simeone, NPR Biography|date=2007-01-09|accessdate=2007-01-09|publisher=National Public Radio}}</ref>\n*[[John C. Wright (author)|John C. Wright]], alumnus and author <ref>of science fiction and fantasy novels; a [[Nebula Award]] finalist for his fantasy novel, ''Orphans of Chaos''. [http://www.sfsite.com/05a/jcw127.htm SF Site \"An Interview with John C. Wright\"]; accessed November 3, 2007</ref>\n\n==== Military Personnel ====\n\n*[[Lewis J. Fields]], [[United States Marine Corps]] [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant general]]<ref name=\"The Washington Posts\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1988/03/08/gen-lj-fields-dies/4cb04ecc-65bd-4fbf-a31a-34ab71b95228/|title=GEN. Lewis J. Fields DIES|work=washingtonpost.com|publisher=The Washington Posts Websites|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n*[[William H. Harrison (USMC)|William H. Harrison]], brigadier general in the Marine Corps during World War II\n*[[Erik S. Kristensen]]; U.S. Navy Seal; attended Graduate Institute in Annapolis; killed in action June 2005\n*[[James B. Lockwood]], American army officer and arctic explorer.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Politicians ====\n\n*[[Joshua J. Cohen]], Mayor of [[Annapolis, Maryland]]\n*[[Clement Dorsey]], Congressman for [[Maryland's 1st congressional district]], 1825\u201331<ref>[http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=D000437 Biographical Directory of the United States Congress] Retrieved on October 27, 2007.</ref>\n*[[Alexander Contee Hanson]], Congressman for [[Maryland's 3rd congressional district|Maryland's 3rd District]], 1813\u20131816<ref>[http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=H000176 Biographical Directory of the United States Congress] Retrieved on October 27, 2007</ref>\n*[[Emerson Harrington]], [[List of Governors of Maryland|Governor of Maryland]]\n*[[Reverdy Johnson]], statesman and Jurist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101217094148/http://millercenter.org/president/taylor/essays/cabinet/244|title=Reverdy Johnson (1849\u20131850): Attorney General|last=Holt|first=Michael|date=|website=American President: An Online Reference Resource.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101217094148/http://millercenter.org/president/taylor/essays/cabinet/244|archive-date=17 December 2010|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[John Leeds Kerr]], U.S. Representative, [[Maryland's 7th congressional district|Maryland's 7th District]]<ref>[http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=K000139 Biographical Directory of the United States Congress] Retrieved on October 28, 2007.</ref>\n*[[Daniel Martin (Governor of Maryland)|Daniel Martin]], [[List of Governors of Maryland|Governor of Maryland]], 1829\u20131830, 1831\n*[[Keith Neville]], [[List of Governors of Nebraska|18th]] [[Governor of Nebraska|Governor]] of [[Nebraska]], 1917\u20131919<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_nebraska/col2-content/main-content-list/title_neville_keith.html|title=Nebraska Governor Keith M. Neville|publisher=National Governors Association|accessdate=September 19, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[William Pinkney]] (1764\u20131822), 7th [[Attorney General of the United States]]\n*[[Ben Sasse]], United States Senator from Nebraska\n*[[Lucy Tamlyn]], U.S. Ambassador to Benin\n*[[Francis Thomas]], [[List of Governors of Maryland|Governor of Maryland]], 1842\u201344; member of House of Representatives, 1861\u201369<ref>[http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=T000166 Biographical Directory of the United States Congress]; retrieved on October 27, 2007.</ref>\n\n==== Filmmakers/Musicians ====\n\n* [[Dimitri Devyatkin]], Emmy-nominated video artist and filmmaker\n* [[Ahmet Erteg\u00fcn]], founded [[Atlantic Records]] in 1947<ref>{{cite news|last=Weiner|first=Tim|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/15/arts/music/15ertegun.html|title=Ahmet Ertegun, Music Executive, Dies at 83|date=December 15, 2006|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2007-10-27}}</ref>\n* [[Jac Holzman]], founded [[Elektra Records]] in 1950 while a student at St. John's<ref>{{cite book|last=Holzman|first=Jac|title=Follow the Music: The Life and High Times of Elektra Records in the Great Years of American Pop Culture|publisher=Jawbone Press|year=2000|isbn=0-9661221-0-0}}</ref>\n* [[Eilen Jewell]], blues and Americana singer/songwriter with five albums (as of 2011)\n* [[Jonathan D. Krane]], film producer, ''[[Look Who's Talking]]'', ''[[Face/Off]]''\n* [[Jeremy Leven]], author, screenwriter and director whose works include ''[[Don Juan DeMarco]]''\n* [[Lhasa de Sela]], singer-songwriter<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Aw4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=%22lhasa+de+sela%22+st+john%27s+college&source=bl&ots=xSnesTOvFh&sig=wY4sMt-ZIl0d3I8EXk89e5kLKmA&hl=en&sa=X&ei=O9WUUMv5H8_UsgapyYHIBA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22lhasa%20de%20sela%22%20st%20john%27s%20college&f=false Profile of de Sela in ''Billboard''], April 12, 1997</ref>\n* [[Glenn Yarbrough]], original lead tenor of [[The Limeliters]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.folkera.com/gyarbrough/bio.html|title=Glenn Yarbrough biography|accessdate=2007-10-27|publisher=Folk Era Records}}</ref>\n* [[Lee David Zlotoff]], creator of ''[[MacGyver (1985 TV series)|MacGyver]]'';<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stjohnscollege.edu/user/MAG_W05_article12.aspx#macgyver|title=MacGyver Meets the Johnnies|date=Winter 2005|accessdate=2007-01-09|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060912012239/http://www.stjohnscollege.edu/user/MAG_W05_article12.aspx#macgyver|archivedate=2006-09-12|publisher=\"The College\", St. John's College}}</ref> director of ''[[The Spitfire Grill]]'' (1996), which won the Audience Award at the [[Sundance Film Festival]]\n\n==== Businesspeople ====\n\n*[[James H. Frame]], computer programming pioneer at IBM, and former vice president of software at ITT; founded James Frame Enterprises (JFE), a software development consulting company\n*[[Eugene V. Thaw]], American art dealer and collector<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cotter|first1=Holland|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/05/obituaries/eugene-v-thaw-dies-art-collector-and-dealer.html|title=Eugene V. Thaw, Influential Art Collector and Dealer, Is Dead at 90|date=January 5, 2018|work=The New York Times|accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Warren Winiarski]], founder of [[Stag's Leap Wine Cellars]]\n\n==== Chefs ====\n\n*[[Daniel Rose (chef)]] Chef with restaurants in Paris (Spring, La Bourse et la Vie) and New York City (Le Coucou)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/20/dining/daniel-rose-chef-le-coucou.html?_r=0&pagewanted=all|title=Daniel Rose, An American in Paris, Comes Home to Cook|date=2016-04-20|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2017-03-28}}</ref>\n*[[Miyoko Schinner]], American chef, cookbook author, animal sanctuary founder and owner of cheese brand [[Miyoko's Creamery]]\n\n==== Others ====\n\n*[[Francis Scott Key]], lyricist of the [[United States of America|United States]] [[national anthem]], ''[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mdhs.org/library/digitalarchives/ssb/ssbaboutssb.shtml|title=Maryland Historical Society Library|accessdate=2007-10-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070413195745/http://www.mdhs.org/library/digitalarchives/ssb/ssbaboutssb.shtml|archivedate=2007-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1886/06/21/106183468.pdf|title=Francis Scott Key's Alma Mater|date=1866-06-21|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2007-10-27}}</ref>\n*[[Charles Van Doren]], garnered notoriety for his involvement in the rigged game show ''[[Twenty One (game show)|Twenty-One]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,895177,00.html|title=College Spawns College|date=December 26, 1960|publisher=[[Time Magazine]]}}</ref>\n\n== Board Members ==\n* [[Austin Ligon]], co-founder/CEO (retired), [[CarMax]], Inc.\n* [[James T. Woodward]], banker and owner of a major [[Thoroughbred]] horse dynasty and member of St. John's board of visitors, recipient of the honorary degree of [[Doctor of Laws]] in 1909;<ref name=NYT>{{cite news\n 